I can write a song.

453
00:25:45,160 --> 00:25:49,221
You already did.
Five minutes, that's all I ask.

454
00:25:50,065 --> 00:25:53,592
Please, step in. You'll enjoy this.
This is a treat.

455
00:25:54,436 --> 00:25:55,903
Mr. Fletcher. Nice to see you.

456
00:25:56,071 --> 00:25:58,471
- Very nice to see you, Mia, how are you?
- Wonderful.

457
00:25:58,640 --> 00:26:01,108
I just want to get...
Can I try the new Mason & Hamlin?

458
00:26:01,276 --> 00:26:04,939
- Sure, absolutely. Be my guest.
- Thank you very much. Thanks. Please.

459
00:26:05,113 --> 00:26:09,379
This is... It's just a little something
that you might possibly recognize.

460
00:26:10,885 --> 00:26:14,082
<i>Figuring out you and me</i>

461
00:26:14,256 --> 00:26:18,886
<i>Is like doing a love autopsy</i>

462
00:26:19,060 --> 00:26:22,029
<i>They could operate all day long</i>

463
00:26:22,197 --> 00:26:25,758
<i>And never figure out what went wrong</i>

464
00:26:27,002 --> 00:26:29,232
<i>Love autopsy</i>

465
00:26:30,872 --> 00:26:32,999
<i>Love autopsy</i>

466
00:26:41,316 --> 00:26:44,080
<i>What went wrong?</i>

467
00:26:49,958 --> 00:26:52,984
God. That melody is so beautiful.

468
00:26:53,161 --> 00:26:55,152
But I've never written a song.

469
00:26:55,330 --> 00:26:57,730
A song. I know, I know.
And if I'm wrong, I'm wrong.

470
00:26:57,899 --> 00:27:01,926
I just don't think I am.
I think you may be a born lyricist.

471
00:27:04,539 --> 00:27:07,736
We don't have very long,
but what I'd like to do, in an ideal world...

472
00:27:07,909 --> 00:27:09,501
...is continue the "Autopsy" song.

473
00:27:09,678 --> 00:27:12,476
But I think it's gonna be very hard
to get back from there...

474
00:27:12,647 --> 00:27:15,707
...into "Way Back Into Love,"
which is the title that Cora demands.

475
00:27:15,884 --> 00:27:19,650
What we could do is continue
with Greg "the Angel of Death's" version.

476
00:27:19,821 --> 00:27:21,186
That's plagiarism.

477
00:27:21,356 --> 00:27:23,449
Yes. Yes, yes. Good. Excellent.

478
00:27:23,625 --> 00:27:26,219
I would never in a million years
use someone else's work.

479
00:27:26,394 --> 00:27:27,588
I'm very glad you agree.

480
00:27:27,762 --> 00:27:33,359
So, what we need,
we need something brand-new.

481
00:27:34,469 --> 00:27:37,870
- So let's see. A song for Cora.
- Yes.

482
00:27:38,039 --> 00:27:41,839
- Has to be called "A Way Back Into Love."
- Correct.

483
00:27:42,010 --> 00:27:44,308
And it has to be something
Cora would sing about.

484
00:27:44,479 --> 00:27:45,741
Good.

485
00:27:45,914 --> 00:27:48,075
And it has to be something
you would sing about.

486
00:27:48,249 --> 00:27:49,409
Good, yeah.

487
00:27:49,584 --> 00:27:52,747
- What would you sing about?
- Whatever gets me the job, really.

488
00:27:53,321 --> 00:27:55,687
Oh, that's inspiring.

489
00:28:01,062 --> 00:28:05,499
Okay. Two people
searching for love, for salvation.

490
00:28:05,667 --> 00:28:06,964
Good, good, I love that.

491
00:28:07,135 --> 00:28:10,502
Love lost, love found.

492
00:28:11,139 --> 00:28:12,470
Love lost again.

493
00:28:12,640 --> 00:28:16,269
Yes, this is starting to sound
a little bit like luggage, but good.

494
00:28:34,963 --> 00:28:36,521
Thanks. That's really helpful.

495
00:28:37,132 --> 00:28:39,464
It doesn't have to be perfect.
Just spit it out.

496
00:28:39,634 --> 00:28:42,034
- They're just lyrics.
- "Just lyrics"?

497
00:28:43,037 --> 00:28:46,666
Lyrics are important.
They're just not as important as melody.

498
00:28:48,009 --> 00:28:49,670
I really don't think you get it.

499
00:28:50,145 --> 00:28:52,010
Oh, you look angry. Click your pen.

500
00:28:52,180 --> 00:28:55,115
A melody is like seeing someone
for the first time.

501
00:28:55,283 --> 00:28:57,148
The physical attraction. Sex.

502
00:28:57,752 --> 00:28:59,617
I so get that.

503
00:28:59,788 --> 00:29:02,916
But then, as you get to know the person,
that's the lyrics.

504
00:29:03,091 --> 00:29:05,719
Their story. Who they are underneath.

505
00:29:06,394 --> 00:29:10,660
It's the combination of the two
that makes it magic.

506
00:29:10,832 --> 00:29:12,424
Let's go for a walk.

507
00:29:12,600 --> 00:29:15,569
- A walk? What, now?
- Yeah.

508
00:29:15,737 --> 00:29:20,071
Out on the streets you see things
and, you know, hear things and eat things.

509
00:29:20,241 --> 00:29:22,732
It all sort of unlocks your mind.

510
00:29:27,449 --> 00:29:29,110
This is good. This is good.

511
00:29:29,284 --> 00:29:31,548
When you hit a wall,
you gotta change the subject.

512
00:29:31,719 --> 00:29:33,016
So why did PoP break up?

513
00:29:33,188 --> 00:29:35,986
I mean, Rhonda told me
that you guys were friends growing up?

514
00:29:36,157 --> 00:29:38,489
We were, yes,
and then Colin met a new manager...

515
00:29:38,660 --> 00:29:40,890
...who convinced him
he was the star of the band.

516
00:29:41,062 --> 00:29:44,554
Shortly after, he left, taking the last
three songs we'd written together...

517
00:29:44,732 --> 00:29:48,498
...and putting them on his solo album
which went on to sell eight million records.

518
00:29:48,670 --> 00:29:51,332
But how did you deal with that?

519
00:29:51,506 --> 00:29:53,440
Oh, with drugs, alcohol...

520
00:29:53,608 --> 00:29:57,635
...and ultimately, my own solo album.

521
00:30:02,350 --> 00:30:03,578
Cool.

522
00:30:03,751 --> 00:30:06,311
This copy has been in the racks
for six years.

523
00:30:06,488 --> 00:30:08,217
- Come on.
- No, no. I check every week.

524
00:30:08,389 --> 00:30:10,857
You see, I made a little mark,
there on the back. See?

525
00:30:11,025 --> 00:30:13,858
It sold only 50,000 copies,
most of those to my mother.

526
00:30:14,028 --> 00:30:16,588
<i>Rolling Stone</i> called it
"a crass, contrived effort...

527
00:30:16,764 --> 00:30:19,289
...not even good enough
for a dentist chair."

528
00:30:20,768 --> 00:30:22,963
Well, I'm sure there were other reviews.

529
00:30:23,137 --> 00:30:25,537
There were, there were.
But none as good as that one.

530
00:30:25,707 --> 00:30:27,641
And they were right, by the way. Yeah.

531
00:30:30,111 --> 00:30:32,636
To cut a long story short,
I gave up trying to write...

532
00:30:32,814 --> 00:30:35,578
...lost an incredible amount of money
and then my apartment.

533
00:30:35,750 --> 00:30:38,776
Chris stuck by me, booked me
an '80s reunion night on Long Island.

534
00:30:38,953 --> 00:30:41,046
And suddenly, they liked me again.

535
00:30:41,222 --> 00:30:43,452
It was weird.
It was like I'd never been away.

536
00:30:43,625 --> 00:30:45,525
The audience was a tad older, as was I...

537
00:30:45,693 --> 00:30:48,958
...but we were very, very profoundly happy
to see each other again.

538
00:30:49,130 --> 00:30:51,963
And it went on from there.

539
00:30:52,133 --> 00:30:55,660
Cruises. Reunions. Knott's Berry Farm,
which I'm sure you're familiar with.

540
00:30:55,837 --> 00:30:59,534
Busch Gardens,
that's one of my big fixtures of the year.

541
00:30:59,707 --> 00:31:01,038
What else can I tell you?

542
00:31:01,209 --> 00:31:04,736
I really appreciate
you opening up to me like this.

543
00:31:06,180 --> 00:31:09,308
I know what it's like
to live with a shadow overhead.

544
00:31:13,021 --> 00:31:14,249
What?

545
00:31:16,624 --> 00:31:17,818
Shadow.

546
00:31:18,459 --> 00:31:23,123
<i>I've been living with a shadow overhead</i>

547
00:31:24,065 --> 00:31:26,295
Now, that's a nice melody, isn't it?

548
00:31:26,467 --> 00:31:28,264
- It's good.
- Thank you. Thank you.

549
00:31:28,436 --> 00:31:30,961
Mind you, what do you know?
You don't even like melody.

550
00:31:31,139 --> 00:31:32,800
I never said that.

551
00:31:32,974 --> 00:31:34,874
You prefer the lyrics.

552
00:31:35,043 --> 00:31:36,101
I don't trust you.

553
00:31:36,277 --> 00:31:37,642
Your turn, what's next?

554
00:31:38,613 --> 00:31:40,945
I think that we should get
some breakfast.

555
00:31:41,115 --> 00:31:43,913
Please, come on, we're finally
on a roll here. Listen again.

556
00:31:44,085 --> 00:31:47,851
<i>I've been living with a shadow overhead</i>

557
00:31:48,022 --> 00:31:51,185
<i>There'll be no more rhymes until I'm fed</i>

558
00:31:51,359 --> 00:31:52,883
Please, seriously, seriously.

559
00:31:53,061 --> 00:31:55,154
<i>I've been living with a shadow overhead</i>

560
00:31:55,330 --> 00:31:58,163
<i>I could be inspired</i>
<i>With just a piece of bread</i>

561
00:31:58,900 --> 00:32:00,959
- I have the perfect place.
- Wait a minute.

562
00:32:01,135 --> 00:32:02,466
It's just on the next corner.

563
00:32:02,637 --> 00:32:04,537
- Keep moving and keep writing.
- All right.

564
00:32:04,706 --> 00:32:08,267
<i>I've been looking</i>
<i>For someone to shed some light</i>

565
00:32:08,810 --> 00:32:10,607
- That's good. That's good.
- Yeah?

566
00:32:10,778 --> 00:32:12,643
Shadows and light. You're deep.

567
00:32:12,814 --> 00:32:15,647
Okay, we need two more lines
of Cora verse. What's next?

568
00:32:15,817 --> 00:32:17,148
Soph?

569
00:32:20,054 --> 00:32:21,043
Sophie?

570
00:32:22,557 --> 00:32:24,149
What are you doing?

571
00:32:24,325 --> 00:32:25,724
Nothing.

572
00:32:25,893 --> 00:32:29,886
I thought I saw someone,
but it wasn't him. So it's fine.

573
00:32:30,064 --> 00:32:33,465
- Oh, there he is.
- What?

574
00:32:33,635 --> 00:32:36,604
A very nice picture, though.
That's funny.

575
00:32:37,372 --> 00:32:40,705
Interestingly enough, I mean...
Well, it is a bookstore.

576
00:32:40,875 --> 00:32:43,036
- So, you know, that does happen.
- What?

577
00:32:44,612 --> 00:32:46,603
Gosh, where were we? Okay.

578
00:32:46,781 --> 00:32:48,078
<i>Shadow overhead</i>

579
00:32:48,249 --> 00:32:52,083
Okay, can I just say, with all due respect,
that you are clearly...

580
00:32:52,253 --> 00:32:54,221
What is the word?
- Insane at this moment.

581
00:32:54,389 --> 00:32:57,222
And because, according to Chris,
we have less than 36 hours...

582
00:32:57,392 --> 00:33:00,520
...before Cora goes to do <i>Leno</i>,
at which point my career is over...

583
00:33:00,695 --> 00:33:06,099
...it would be infinitely better for me
if you were sane. So how can I help?

584
00:33:08,970 --> 00:33:10,130
Do you know this book?

585
00:33:13,041 --> 00:33:16,272
<i>Sally Michaels?</i> Yes, yes.
Big bestseller. Yes.

586
00:33:16,444 --> 00:33:18,537
- Have you read it?
- No, of course not.

587
00:33:18,713 --> 00:33:22,774
Last book I read was <i>The Alex Fletcher Story</i>
by the editors of <i>Teen Dream Magazine.</i>

588
00:33:24,819 --> 00:33:26,286
Why?

589
00:33:30,825 --> 00:33:33,919
I'm Sally Michaels.

590
00:33:36,497 --> 00:33:40,024
<i>I saw that they were giving these courses</i>
<i>on writing at the New School...</i>

591
00:33:40,201 --> 00:33:42,192
<i>... so I signed up.</i>

592
00:33:42,370 --> 00:33:45,771
<i>And my teacher was Sloan Cates.</i>

593
00:33:45,940 --> 00:33:47,931
<i>Nrilliant, handsome.</i>

594
00:33:48,109 --> 00:33:51,340
The truth is, I was in love with him.

595
00:33:52,113 --> 00:33:54,138
And we began spending
every minute together.

596
00:33:54,315 --> 00:33:58,115
Which is why I was sort of surprised
when his fiancée showed up.

597
00:33:59,387 --> 00:34:02,914
Yeah, he never mentioned that
he was engaged to a history professor...

598
00:34:03,091 --> 00:34:05,525
...who was on a year-long sabbatical
in Spain.

599
00:34:05,693 --> 00:34:08,184
And when she popped in
for an unexpected visit...

600
00:34:08,362 --> 00:34:11,957
...it sort of turned into a reenactment
of the Inquisition.

601
00:34:12,400 --> 00:34:14,925
And that... And that was that?
That was the end of that?

602
00:34:15,103 --> 00:34:17,196
Yeah. We never saw each other again.

603
00:34:17,371 --> 00:34:20,602
I dropped the class and a year later,
his new novel showed up.

604
00:34:21,008 --> 00:34:22,839
The Sally What's-it novel.

605
00:34:23,010 --> 00:34:25,740
"The tale of a student
with exalted literary aspirations...

606
00:34:25,913 --> 00:34:30,213
...who lures a brilliant writer into an affair
so she can take advantage of his connections.

607
00:34:30,718 --> 00:34:35,052
But when he tries to break it off,
she devotes herself to ruining his life."

608
00:34:35,389 --> 00:34:37,721
Well, I mean, that obviously wasn't you.

609
00:34:38,826 --> 00:34:44,662
Well, she's a lit major from Long Island,
5'4", my color hair, all my habits.

610
00:34:44,832 --> 00:34:47,858
You know, talks to herself
and asks too many questions.

611
00:34:48,035 --> 00:34:50,469
Her parents founded
a weight reduction company...

612
00:34:50,638 --> 00:34:52,401
...that now her sister runs.

613
00:34:52,807 --> 00:34:54,741
Well, anyway, I...

614
00:34:55,476 --> 00:34:58,172
Since then, every time I pick up a pen...

615
00:34:58,346 --> 00:35:01,747
...l'm haunted by those words
that he wrote, you know?

616
00:35:01,916 --> 00:35:04,942
"She was a brilliant mimic." You know.

617
00:35:05,119 --> 00:35:07,917
"She could ape Dorothy Parker
or Emily Dickinson...

618
00:35:08,089 --> 00:35:11,252
...but stripped of someone else's
literary clothes...

619
00:35:11,425 --> 00:35:15,828
...she was a vacant,
empty imitation of a writer."

620
00:35:16,731 --> 00:35:19,723
First of all, you can't listen to some jerk.

621
00:35:20,234 --> 00:35:23,601
He's not a jerk.
He's a National Book Award winner.

622
00:35:23,771 --> 00:35:27,172
Well, then, get the best revenge,
write a hit song.

623
00:35:28,075 --> 00:35:31,272
Honestly, I don't think a pop song
is gonna impress Sloan Cates.

624
00:35:31,679 --> 00:35:34,477
Oh, no, of course not.
Pop is just for morons. Forgot that.

625
00:35:34,649 --> 00:35:37,914
- I didn't mean anything by it.
- Brain-dead, or taken too many drugs.

626
00:35:38,085 --> 00:35:40,110
You know what I'd say
to you and Sloan Cates?

627
00:35:40,288 --> 00:35:42,449
You can take all the novels
in the world...

628
00:35:42,623 --> 00:35:45,854
...and not one of them
will make you feel as good as fast as:

629
00:35:52,733 --> 00:35:54,701
That is real poetry. Those are real poets.

630
00:35:54,869 --> 00:35:58,896
Smokey Robinson, Stevie Wonder,
Bob Dylan, the Beatles.

631
00:35:59,073 --> 00:36:03,032
Okay. What if one of your heroes
came up to you and said...

632
00:36:03,211 --> 00:36:05,771
You know, Smokey, what if he said:

633
00:36:05,947 --> 00:36:09,747
"Alex Fletcher,
you are a horrible songwriter"?

634
00:36:09,917 --> 00:36:10,906
How would you react?

635
00:36:11,085 --> 00:36:14,748
I know Smokey a little bit. He's too nice
a gentleman ever to say such a thing.

636
00:36:15,823 --> 00:36:19,088
Dylan might. Dylan would, actually.
In fact, Dylan did.

637
00:36:19,260 --> 00:36:24,129
Okay, Dylan walks up to you and he says,
"You are a horrible songwriter."

638
00:36:25,499 --> 00:36:27,797
- How do you react?
- I would be horribly depressed.

639
00:36:27,969 --> 00:36:30,597
Yes. I would. I would.

640
00:36:30,771 --> 00:36:34,434
But then, after, you know,
months of brooding...

641
00:36:34,609 --> 00:36:37,442
...I would find a lyricist...

642
00:36:38,112 --> 00:36:41,707
...and write a song
about how horribly depressed I was.

643
00:36:41,883 --> 00:36:45,512
And it would be a big hit, everyone
would love me, and I'd make lots of money.

644
00:36:45,686 --> 00:36:48,382
Suddenly I'd be less depressed
than if I just sat around...

645
00:36:48,556 --> 00:36:51,923
...being a little bit self-indulgent,
letting my misery eat away at me...

646
00:36:52,093 --> 00:36:56,996
...until I'd become an emotional wreck
and creatively completely moribund.

647
00:36:59,333 --> 00:37:01,096
Yes, moribund.

648
00:37:05,473 --> 00:37:07,134
- Okay, let's go. Come on.
- All right.

649
00:37:07,775 --> 00:37:11,541
<i>I've been living with a shadow overhead</i>

650
00:37:11,712 --> 00:37:15,648
<i>I've been sleeping</i>
<i>With a clown above my bed</i>

651
00:37:15,816 --> 00:37:18,376
- "Clown" is not right. What is that word?
- It's "cloud."

652
00:37:18,552 --> 00:37:22,079
- Write more clearly. How can l...?
- Why would you have a clown in your bed?

653
00:37:22,256 --> 00:37:24,918
- It would not be the first time.
- Yeah, I'm not surprised.

654
00:37:25,092 --> 00:37:27,492
- Write in capital letters.
- Why don't you write it?

655
00:37:27,662 --> 00:37:30,096
I'm sorry, Khan.
We're gonna come back in one second.

656
00:37:30,264 --> 00:37:32,994
You dictate, I'll write.
And I will write like a human...

657
00:37:33,167 --> 00:37:35,226
...and not like a small Pekingese dog.

658
00:37:35,403 --> 00:37:38,531
What are you doing, you madwoman?
You're destroying my apartment.

659
00:37:38,706 --> 00:37:40,970
I can't write from across the room.

660
00:37:41,142 --> 00:37:43,940
Well, you're not writing here.
Get back to your corner.

661
00:37:44,111 --> 00:37:45,100
I can't have you here.

662
00:37:45,279 --> 00:37:48,737
- I'll be blocked. I'll be completely stuck.
- So go out the other side.

663
00:37:48,916 --> 00:37:50,975
I've never been the other side.

664
00:37:51,852 --> 00:37:55,151
Push, push. Push, push.

665
00:38:00,461 --> 00:38:02,588
Good. Better.

666
00:38:02,763 --> 00:38:05,891
You're still a fraction close.
Just... Just back off, just one...

667
00:38:06,067 --> 00:38:07,557
Just... Just...

668
00:38:07,735 --> 00:38:09,202
There, fine, good.

669
00:38:09,370 --> 00:38:10,860
Okay.

670
00:38:27,054 --> 00:38:29,887
And I don't think those chords are right.

671
00:38:30,057 --> 00:38:32,924
It has to sound different than the verse.

672
00:38:33,327 --> 00:38:35,318
What kind of different
did you have in mind?

673
00:38:35,496 --> 00:38:38,260
I don't know.
Something sadder, you know?

674
00:38:38,432 --> 00:38:41,663
And I still don't like my line
about "places in my mind."

675
00:38:41,836 --> 00:38:45,033
- It's fine.
- Fine isn't good.

676
00:38:45,206 --> 00:38:46,730
We only have time for fine.

677
00:38:46,907 --> 00:38:49,341
I tell you what.
We'll change "places in my mind"...

678
00:38:49,510 --> 00:38:51,910
...if I can keep the chord sequence
into the bridge.

679
00:38:52,079 --> 00:38:53,512
This isn't a negotiation.

680
00:38:53,681 --> 00:38:56,809
It's either right or wrong,
